<subSubSection pageId="26" pageNumber="27" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1437,1410,1653]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,1554,1580]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Distribution.</emphasis>
This species was previously recorded from 
<collectingCountry box="[839,984,1554,1580]" name="Saudi Arabia" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Saudi Arabia</collectingCountry>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Abu-Zoherah, R. &amp; Al-Taher, K. &amp; Tilkian, S." box="[1022,1319,1554,1581]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" refId="ref29552" refString="Abu-Zoherah, R., Al-Taher, K. &amp; Tilkian, S. (1993) List of Insects Recorded from Saudi Arabia. Ministry of Agriculture and Water, National Agriculture and Water Research Centre, Kingdom of Saudi Arabia, Riyadh, 394 pp." type="book" year="1993">
Abu-Zoherah 
<emphasis box="[1179,1227,1554,1580]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">et al</emphasis>
. (1993)
</bibRefCitation>
. It was described from 
<collectingCountry box="[300,399,1590,1616]" name="Ethiopia" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Ethiopia</collectingCountry>
. It was recoded from 
<collectingCountry box="[639,717,1591,1617]" name="Yemen" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Yemen</collectingCountry>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="van Emden, F. I." box="[759,971,1590,1617]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" pagination="161 - 175" refId="ref37148" refString="van Emden, F. I. (1948) Diptera: Muscidae. In: Expedition to South-West Arabia 1937 - 1938. Vol. I. British Museum (Natural History), London, pp. 161 - 175." type="book chapter" year="1948">van Emden (1948)</bibRefCitation>
. The identification of van Emden’s specimens of this species was confirmed by J.C. Deeming (
<bibRefCitation author="Pont, A. C." box="[758,933,1626,1652]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" refId="ref35020" refString="Pont, A. C. (1991) A review of the Fanniidae and Muscidae (Diptera) of the Arabian Peninsula. Fauna of Saudi Arabia, 12, 312 - 265." type="book" year="1991">Pont 1991: 342</bibRefCitation>
) as the identification was in some doubt.
</paragraph>
